org.snrg_nyc.model

Interface PropertiesEditor

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    EditorTester
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    NodeEditor

    public interface PropertiesEditor
    The public-facing business logic for use by the user interface of an SNRG frontend. This interface and any implementations of it should be the only classes used outside of the model packages.
    Version:
    0.2
    Author:
    Devin Hastings

      Check if the scratch property can use distributions (regardless of the number of distributions).

        int scratch_addConditionalDistribution(java.util.Map<java.lang.Integer,java.lang.Integer> dependencyConditions,
                                       java.util.Map<java.lang.Integer,java.lang.Float> probabilities)
                                throws EditorException
        Add a conditional Distribution to the current scratch property

        probabilities - See scratch_addConditionalDistribution(java.util.Map<java.lang.Integer, java.lang.Integer>, java.util.Map<java.lang.Integer, java.lang.Float>) for requirements
        Throws:
        EditorException - Thrown if the ID does not point to a distribution, or the requirements for the parameters are not met , or if the scratch property is currently null, which means scratch_new(String, String, String) needs to be called.

      • scratch_commit

        int scratch_commit()
            throws EditorException
        Finalize the scratch property and add it to the structure of node properties. In its current state, this clears the scratch property automatically, and there is no way to edit or remove an added node property, so it is important to make sure the property is how the user wants it before committing.

        If the scratch property was created using scratch_newInLayer(int, java.lang.String, java.lang.String, java.lang.String), it will be attached to the layer using the layer ID that was used there. Call scratch_getLayerID() to see what layer it will be attached to.

        Returns:
        The node property ID of the new property, which is also available through nodeProp_getPropertyIDs()
        Throws:
        EditorException - There are several reasons that this exception may be thrown, here is a list of examples:
        • The scratch property is null, which means scratch_new(String, String, String) was never called
        • The scratch property has the same name as another node property
        • The scratch property is ranged, but does not have a default distribution set.
        • The property was created using scratch_newInLayer(int, String, String, String), and the layer linked to the given ID was removed, which should not be possible from this interface.
        And various other messages. Throwable.getMessage() should yield more information.
